                rend="superscript">th</hi>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">1815</hi>.-<lb/>
-. The effects produced when concentrated <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">hydro</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#chemical_417"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag11">
          sulphuric<lb/>acid
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">the</del>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag12"
                ref="#chemical_087"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag12">
          oil of Vitriol
          
        </term>
            </rs> is poured upon <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag13"
                ref="#chemical_432"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag13">
          hyperoxymuriate
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag14"
                ref="#chemical_436"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag14">
          Potassa
          
        </term>
            </rs> have been often objects of chemical<lb/>
discussion, the acid &amp; the salt it is well<lb/>
known becne deep orange <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">&amp;</add> , if any moisture is<lb/>
present <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a detonation occurs</del>: or if heat<lb/>
is applied to the mixture a detonation<lb/>
occurs - In a paper read before<lb/>
the Royal Society I have ventured to<lb/>
suppose that these phaenomena depend upon<lb/>
the developement &amp; <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">d</del> sudden decomposition<lb/>
of the compound of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag15"
                ref="#chemical_303"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag15">
          chlorine
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag16"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag16">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
which I have named <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag17"
                ref="#chemical_307"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag17">
          Euchlorine
          
        </term>
            </rs>.<lb/>
A statement which I understand has been<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">In examining the phaenomena of the action</del>
            <lb/>
made of by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag18"
                ref="#person_012"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag18" type="person">
          M. Gay Lussac
        </name>
            </rs> namely that a peculiar<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of acids on the <rs xml:id="ttag19" ref="#chemical_432" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag19">
          hyperoxymuriates
          
        </term>
               </rs> with</del>
            <lb/>
acid which he has called chloric acid may<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="26"
                xml:id="pb-26"
                facs="#i26"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">2</hi> 2<lb/>
he procured from the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag20"
                ref="#chemical_432"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag20">
          hyperoxymuriate
          
        </term>
            </rs> of<lb/>
Baryta by Sulpheric acid led me to<lb/>
examine the action of acids on the hyproxymuriates<lb/>
under new circumstances &amp; I have made<lb/>
some observations which appear to me<lb/>
not unworthy of being communicated<lb/>
to the Royal Society.<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">-. At the line that <rs xml:id="ttag21" ref="#chemical_432" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag21">
          hyperoxymuriate
          
        </term>
               </rs>
            </del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">of <rs xml:id="ttag22" ref="#chemical_436" type="chemical">
                  <term xml:id="tag22">
          Potassa
          
        </term>
               </rs> is he</del>
            <lb/>
If <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">30 or 40 pts of</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag23"
                ref="#chemical_417"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag23">
          Sulphuric acid
          
        </term>
            </rs> be poured upon<lb/>
dry <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag24"
                ref="#chemical_430"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag24">
          hyperoxymuriate of potassa
          
        </term>
            </rs> in <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">a glass</del>
            <lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">common</del> wine glass &amp; the salt be<lb/>
agitated in the acid, there is a<lb/>
very slight effervescence only, the acid<lb/>
becomes of a deep orange tint<lb/>
&amp; white fumes mixed with orange fumes<lb/>
fill the upper part of the glass<lb/>
which have a very peculiar<lb/>
&amp; not a disagreable smell.-<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="27"
                xml:id="pb-27"
                facs="#i27"/>
            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">3</hi>
            <lb/>
- The slight effervescence taking place in<lb/>
this process induced me to suppose that<lb/>
the substance which coloured the acid<lb/>
must contain a larger proportion of<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag25"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag25">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs> than <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag26"
                ref="#chemical_307"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag26">
          Euchlorine
          
        </term>
            </rs> for I have shewn<lb/>
in a work published in 1812 that <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag27"
                ref="#chemical_432"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag27">
          hyperoxymuriate
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag28"
                ref="#chemical_436"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag28">
          Potassa
          
        </term>
            </rs> contains 6 proportions of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag29"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag29">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
&amp; by its decomposition <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">3</del> 2.5 volumes of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
