                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag33">
          hyperoxymuriate of potassa
          
        </term>
            </rs> by <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">solution of</add>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag34"
                ref="#chemical_016"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag34">
          Muriatic<lb/>acid
          
        </term>
            </rs> yields only 1 Volume of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag35"
                ref="#chemical_022"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag35">
          Oxygene
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
&amp; 2 volumes of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag36"
                ref="#chemical_303"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag36">
          chlorine
          
        </term>
            </rs>.<lb/>
- I endeavored to procure the substance<lb/>
which coloured the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag37"
                ref="#chemical_417"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag37">
          Sulphuric acid
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
during its action upon <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag38"
                ref="#chemical_432"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag38">
          hyperoxymuriate
          
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag39"
                ref="#chemical_436"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag39">
          Potassa
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; after several failures<lb/>
in which explosions took place<lb/>
I at length succeeded in the<lb/>
