                 rend="strikethrough">16</del> 28 98<lb/>
It does not appear by what I have learnt from all the miners<lb/>
that breathing an atmosphere containing a certain mixture<lb/>
of fire damp * below the explosive point is attended with<lb/>
any bad consequence .- I ascertained that a bird lived in a mix-<lb/>
ture of equal parts of fire damp and air but he soon began to<lb/>
shew symptoms of suffering I found a slight head ache produced<lb/>
by breathing for a few minutes an explosive mixture of fire<lb/>
damp and air and if merely the health of the miners be<lb/>
considered the fire damp ought always to be kept far below the<lb/>
point of its explosive mixture.<lb/>
Miners sometimes are sometimes found alive in a mine after <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">its</del>
            <lb/>
an explosion has taken place this is easily explained when it<lb/>
