I have had two other <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">close</add> lanterns made which<lb/>
may be called the fire valve lanterns.<lb/>
In this the candle or lamp burns<lb/>
with its full quantity of air, till<lb/>
the air begins to be mixed<lb/>
with fire damp when as the<lb/>
fire damp increases the flame<lb/>
a thermometrical spring at the top<lb/>
of the lantern made of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag535"
                ref="#chemical_321"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag535">
          Brass
          
        </term>
            </rs> &amp; <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag536"
                ref="#chemical_323"
                type="chemical">
               <term xml:id="tag536">
          Steel
          
        </term>
            </rs> soldered<lb/>
together &amp; in a curved form <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">expands</add> moves<lb/>
a valve which may be either at<lb/>
the air hole or the chimney<lb/>
diminishes the circulation of air<lb/>
&amp; extinguishes the flame.<lb/>
The fire valve lanterns probably will never<lb/>
be necessary in coal mines unless there<lb/>
should be found instanced in which<lb/>
