of cold air <del rend="strikethrough">thrown</del> thrown upon<lb/>
a small flame lowers its heat<lb/>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="161" xml:id="pb-161" facs="#i161"/>
               <lb/>
7 133<lb/>
beyond the explosive point: &amp; in extinguishing<lb/>
a flame by blowing upon it<lb/>
the effect is probably principally<lb/>
produced by this cause assisted<lb/>
               <del rend="strikethrough">probably</del> by a dilution of the<lb/>
explosive mixture. -<lb/>
- If a piece of wire gauze sieve<lb/>
is held over a flame of<lb/>
a lamp or of coal gas, it prevents<lb/>
the flame from passing it &amp; the<lb/>
phenomenon is precisely similar<lb/>
to that exhibited by the wire<lb/>
